public class ReserveLine
extends com.guidewire.pl.persistence.code.BeanBase
implements Retireable, Extractable, TAccountOwnerDelegate
    ReserveLine A combination of Claim, Exposure, CostType, and CostCategory, used to categorize every Transaction on a claim. Every Transaction has a ReserveLine. Claim is required, as all Transactions must be associated with a Claim. Exposure can be NULL, in which case the Transaction and ReserveLine are "Claim-level". CostType and CostCategory are typelists that contain values for categorizing Transactions, which can be configured for the customer's needs. CostType and CostCategory cannot be NULL, but each has an Unspecified value (which may be removed during configuration).

    Every Transaction either increases or depletes reserves on a ReserveLine. Given the flexibility of Exposure being null, and the two typelists being configurable, customers can track their Transactions according to their needs: all Reserves and Payments could occur at the claim-level, or they could be categorized by exposure, CostType ("ClaimCost", "A & O" adjusting expenses, etc) and CostCategory (Auto body repair, Legal, Vehicle Inspection, etc). Only certain combinations of Exposure coverage type, CostType, and CostCategory are valid, as defined in the CostCategory.xml typelist file.

      • getPaymentsIterator

        public java.util.Iterator<Payment> getPaymentsIterator(boolean newAndModifiedOnly)

        Constructs an Iterator to provide access to the Payment objects for this reserveline. You can choose to get either all the payments or only the new and modified payments. If you choose to get all the Payment objects, then Payment objects in the current transaction are not be returned by the Iterator. This method is a much more efficient alternative to calling getTransactions() and iterating through all the transactions to find just the desired Payment objects.

        Note: When newAndModifiedOnly is false, the beans returned by this iterator are not guaranteed to be in the same bundle as this ReserveLine, and their bundle may not be editable. To edit the beans, you should add them to an editable bundle first.

        Parameters:
        newAndModifiedOnly - if true then only new and modified Payment objects for this reserveline are returned. This includes payments for which only the line items were modified. Otherwise, if false then all Payment objects for the reserveline are returned, including new and modified Payment objects, but excluding deleted Payment objects.
        Returns:
        an Iterator that returns Payment objects.

      • getTransactionsIterator

        public java.util.Iterator<Transaction> getTransactionsIterator(boolean newAndModifiedOnly)

        Constructs an Iterator to provide access to the transactions for this reserveline. This is a more efficient alternative to calling getTransactions(), particularly if you are only interested in new or modified transactions. You can use this method to retrieve all the Transaction objects or only the new and modified objects. If you choose to retrieve all the Transaction objects then, those transactions that were removed in the current transaction are not be returned by the Iterator.

        Note: When newAndModifiedOnly is false, there is no guarantee that the beans returned by this iterator may not be in the same bundle as this ReserveLine, and their bundle may not be editable. To edit the beans, you should add them to an editable bundle first.

        Parameters:
        newAndModifiedOnly - if true then only new and modified transactions for this reserveline are returned. This includes transactions for which only the line items were modified. Otherwise, if false then the method returns all transactions for the reserveline, including new and modified Transaction objects, but excluding deleted transactions.
        Returns:
        an Iterator that returns transactions.

        public java.lang.Boolean isRetired()
        Specified by:
        isRetired in interface Retireable
        Returns:
        True if the object has been retired from active use, false if the object is active. Retireable objects are never deleted from a database table, instead they are retired by setting the retired column to the same value as the ID of the object.

      • refresh

        public KeyableBean refresh()
        Refreshes this bean with the latest database version.

        This method does nothing if the bean is edited or inserted in its current bundle. If the bean no longer exists in the database, then null is returned. If the bean has been evicted from its bundle, then null is returned. Otherwise, this bean is returned, with its contents updated.

        Specified by:
        refresh in interface Editable
        Specified by:
        refresh in interface KeyableBean
        Specified by:
        refresh in interface Retireable
        Specified by:
        refresh in interface Versionable

      • remove

        public void remove()
        Marks this bean for remove. A bean marked for remove will be deleted or retired when the transaction is committed. Once a bean is marked for remove, it cannot be switched to update, edit, or read.

        WARNING: This method is designed for simple custom entities which are normally not associated with other entities. Undesirable results may occur when used on out-of-box entities.

        Specified by:
        remove in interface Editable

      • touch

        public void touch()
        Set's the version of the bean to the next value (i.e. the bean version original value+1) Multiple calls to this method on the same bean will result in the same value being used for the version (i.e. it is idempotent). Calling this method will force the bean to be written to the database and participate fully in the commit cycle e.g. pre-update rules will be run, etc.
        Specified by:
        touch in interface Editable
        Specified by:
        touch in interface Retireable
        Specified by:
        touch in interface Versionable
